101
00:07:26.815 --> 00:07:30.987
As you can see by the pulse
of the notes above.

102
00:07:30.987 --> 00:07:35.620
Finally, the most sophisticated
example yet, of harmony,

103
00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:38.928
a piece by JS Bach,
a prelude for keyboard.

104
00:07:38.928 --> 00:07:42.109
Here, ironically, there's no melody.

105
00:07:42.109 --> 00:07:43.850
There's just a harmony.

106
00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:53.740
[MUSIC]

107
00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:57.398
But what he's done is taken
those chords of the harmony and

108
00:07:57.398 --> 00:07:59.347
spread them out as arpeggios.

109
00:07:59.347 --> 00:08:09.347
[MUSIC]

110
00:08:17.423 --> 00:08:20.650
This independent harmony does not repeat.

111
00:08:20.650 --> 00:08:25.310
It's not an ostinato bass harmony,
as in our previous two examples.

112
00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:27.130
It unfolds continually.

113
00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:31.180
This is one long chord
progression in the tonality of C.

114
00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:35.310
And I might add that
the original version of this,

115
00:08:35.310 --> 00:08:40.460
arguably one of Bach's most famous
pieces and in Bach's hand, for

116
00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:46.130
the most part is actually in our
own Yale University library.

117
00:08:47.330 --> 00:08:51.400
Bach was trying to teach his first child,
Wilhelm Friedeman Bach, how to play and

118
00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:52.730
how to compose and

119
00:08:52.730 --> 00:08:56.890
here's the way it originally looked as
you see on the left side of the screen.

120
00:08:56.890 --> 00:09:01.590
The hand on the upper left,
that's the hand of the son,

121
00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:05.391
Wilhelm Friedemann, and
Bach came along and

122
00:09:05.391 --> 00:09:10.292
tried to move things along by
just prescribing chords that

123
00:09:10.292 --> 00:09:14.910
should be played toward
the bottom right of the score.

124
00:09:14.910 --> 00:09:19.910
With the implication that they were
to then be executed as arpeggios.

125
00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:25.400
So, again,
this is Bach's harmony without any melody.

126
00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:31.770
But, more than 100 years later
a French composer, Charles Gounod,

127
00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:35.240
came along and
added a melody to Bach's harmony,

128
00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:40.080
the two together being even more rich and
pleasing than Bach's original harmony.

129
00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:43.310
A text was added to it, Ave Maria,

130
00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:47.310
turning it into a religious work,
the Bach Gounod Ave Maria.

131
00:09:48.700 --> 00:09:51.490
And Bach's piece,
originally just a harmony,

132
00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:54.850
is sung today at weddings and
funerals around the world.

